00:09.300 --> 00:13.220
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.960 --> 00:34.320
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.000 --> 00:38.700
And here are your hosts.

00:42.740 --> 00:44.740
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane.

00:44.920 --> 00:49.980
Michael Bishop has written a number of stunning science fiction works, such as the novels Eyes of Fire,

00:50.160 --> 00:56.920
the 1983 Nebula-winning No Enemy But Time, and the Urban Nucleus series, A Little Knowledge and Catacomb Years.

00:57.240 --> 00:59.400
Bishop is also a master at writing short stories.

00:59.600 --> 01:05.980
Some of his outstanding stories are On the Street of Serpents, Death and Designation Among the Asadi, and The White Otters of Childhood.

01:05.980 --> 01:08.680
Fans and fellow writers alike have lauded Bishop.

01:08.920 --> 01:12.200
He has been nominated for some 11 Hugo and Nebula awards.

01:12.480 --> 01:14.220
Bishop's academic training is in English.

01:14.260 --> 01:16.780
We asked him why he writes science fiction rather than mainstream.

01:17.640 --> 01:23.260
Well, the truth is that I have wanted to be a writer since I was in about the eighth grade,

01:23.260 --> 01:27.060
and I did not necessarily want to be a science fiction writer.

01:27.220 --> 01:28.920
I wanted to be just a writer.

01:30.180 --> 01:35.220
The reason that I'm doing science fiction now, or have done primarily science fiction,

01:35.220 --> 01:43.500
is that I was first successful in submitting stories that had a fantastic or a science fictional element,

01:43.980 --> 01:45.380
and in having them sell.

01:45.600 --> 01:51.880
The other stories, the mainstream stories that I wrote, received primarily rejection slips early on.

01:53.820 --> 02:03.200
And as I've said before, I'm kind of like the rat in the experimental cage who goes to the lever and presses it,

02:03.220 --> 02:08.820
and when the food comes out of one particular lever, that's the one he goes back to and continues to press.

02:08.960 --> 02:13.540
And that's the way I have done as far as science fiction goes to some extent.

02:13.540 --> 02:19.420
It's not that I don't care for science fiction, and I'm doing it solely because it was profitable,

02:20.540 --> 02:23.200
or more profitable than the other type of writing,

02:23.780 --> 02:30.700
but simply that I ended up finding very receptive editors in this particular field,

02:31.460 --> 02:34.000
and that accounts for it, more or less.

02:35.260 --> 02:37.580
Science fiction is attractive to Bishop, too,

02:37.720 --> 02:41.280
because it allows him the freedom to write about a number of subjects and situations.

02:41.280 --> 02:48.160
I think that science fiction does permit a writer to deal with just about anything that he or she wishes to deal with.

02:49.580 --> 02:55.380
You can handle contemporary events by projecting them into the future.

02:55.380 --> 02:58.760
You can speculate about the past.

02:58.900 --> 03:01.380
You can speculate about the distant, distant future.

03:01.660 --> 03:04.300
You can speculate about origins and ultimate ends.

03:04.480 --> 03:08.760
So that I think that really science fiction is a tremendously flexible genre,

03:08.780 --> 03:11.040
and that's one of its main attractions to me.

03:11.040 --> 03:13.760
And one of the reasons why I think I continue to write it,

03:13.900 --> 03:18.420
even though I have aspirations to do other things and have done other things.

03:25.840 --> 03:29.960
A Funeral for the Eyes of Fire, Bishop's first novel, came out in 1975.

03:30.580 --> 03:33.480
Its revision, entitled Eyes of Fire, came out in 1980.

03:33.480 --> 03:36.500
This novel relates the conflict between two cultures,

03:36.500 --> 03:39.320
an advanced space-faring culture and a primitive one.

03:39.540 --> 03:44.500
As do many of Bishop's works, this novel carries a heavy, effectively used dose of anthropology.

03:44.760 --> 03:46.920
We asked Bishop about the basis of this book.

03:47.560 --> 03:50.620
It's a parable of some of the things that have happened in our past

03:50.620 --> 03:55.160
and that continue to happen in our relationships to primitive peoples today.

03:55.160 --> 04:01.800
And I probably should put primitive in quotes because that's a term that is frowned upon

04:01.800 --> 04:03.920
in anthropological circles right now.

04:04.380 --> 04:11.640
But at any rate, I do think that it was a kind of dramatic framing of situations

04:11.640 --> 04:15.680
that have taken place in the confrontation between advanced civilizations

04:15.680 --> 04:20.100
and supposedly primitive, in quotes, civilizations.

04:21.280 --> 04:29.560
And it seems to me that in projecting it into a setting on a distant planet,

04:30.520 --> 04:36.620
that I was just kind of presuming that this was the sort of thing that could happen over and over again.

04:36.620 --> 04:46.140
But at the same time, really, it was a comment on the conflict between two different approaches of viewing the world.

04:46.280 --> 04:55.140
One, rather, the technological approach, and one, the rather mystical or, what do you call it, the left brain side.

04:56.100 --> 04:58.380
We'll have more with Michael Bishop on our next show.

