06:36.340 --> 06:38.000
This is Daryl Lane.

06:38.180 --> 06:38.960
And Bill Vernon.

06:39.220 --> 06:43.240
Two closely related works by Michael Bishop are A Little Knowledge and Catacomb Years.

06:43.640 --> 06:47.920
A Little Knowledge is a collection of loosely connected short stories, and Catacomb Years is a novel.

06:48.120 --> 06:51.260
Both are about people who inhabit the urban nucleus of Atlanta,

06:51.720 --> 06:54.680
a future domed Atlanta isolated from the rest of the world.

06:54.680 --> 06:58.080
Here Bishop tells us why he used the concept of a domed city.

06:58.680 --> 07:01.960
Each one of the cities was its own universe, its own world.

07:02.100 --> 07:07.800
The people were withdrawn and isolated, and they practiced the kind of isolationism.

07:07.800 --> 07:13.480
In fact, in the story, "The Windows in Dante's Hell", the old woman, Amelia Longhope,

07:13.580 --> 07:20.800
who is bound by two people who were going to her apartment, really, to discover what's happened to her.

07:22.160 --> 07:26.520
They find that she has created an entire world in her apartment,

07:26.520 --> 07:30.980
which resembles the bridge of a starship, as from an old television program,

07:30.980 --> 07:35.640
and that she has been looking outward while her own society has been looking inward.

07:36.000 --> 07:40.240
So that was one of the things that I was trying to do with the domed city.

07:40.460 --> 07:47.680
I wasn't interested in the domed city as a technological marvel so much as I was in a...

07:48.340 --> 07:52.580
I guess I was looking at each city as a kind of petri dish,

07:52.580 --> 07:58.060
and I was trying to see what the human beings, the bacteria, whatever you want to call them,

07:58.240 --> 08:01.580
inside that petri dish were going to do, how they were going to behave,

08:02.200 --> 08:05.040
and why they were behaving in the ways that they did.

08:05.040 --> 08:14.620
So it was one way of focusing in on the human condition in an unusual way and in a metaphorical way.

08:32.400 --> 08:36.200
A recurring theme in Bishop's work seems to be an emphasis on eyes.

08:36.440 --> 08:39.720
For instance, there's his first novel, A Funeral for the Eyes of Fire.

08:39.960 --> 08:44.500
The Asadi and Transfigurations have prominent eyes which figure significantly in the plot.

08:44.620 --> 08:49.640
The aliens in his first short story, Pinyonfall, have strange multi-lensed eyes.

08:49.900 --> 08:52.480
We asked Bishop about eyes and what they symbolize.

08:53.160 --> 09:00.600
It has always seemed to me that the eyes are, what's the old cliche, the windows of the soul.

09:01.620 --> 09:12.100
And for an alien species, I think they would be similarly a means of looking into the heart of the creature who has those eyes.

09:14.040 --> 09:19.200
I think, too, I was looking early on when I wrote the early story, "Piñon Fall", which was my first story,

09:19.360 --> 09:23.400
I was looking for a way of making my aliens seem alien.

09:23.700 --> 09:26.040
And one of the ways was to describe them physically.

09:26.040 --> 09:32.980
And one of the most outstanding characteristics of any creature, I think, are the eyes

09:32.980 --> 09:35.860
and how they differ from one species to another.

09:36.100 --> 09:39.840
So the aliens in "Piñon Fall" had eyes like insects.

09:41.920 --> 09:46.860
In A Funeral for the Eyes of Fire, I guess I was, again, looking for a means,

09:47.080 --> 09:53.520
an exotic means of establishing the fact that my aliens were truly alien.

09:53.520 --> 10:00.000
And by giving them different eyes, eyes like gems, that was one way of doing that.

10:00.520 --> 10:06.740
There may have been some subliminal influence, too, from one of the novels of Ursula Le Guin.

10:07.800 --> 10:10.540
I'm trying to think now, which was A City of Illusions.

10:10.900 --> 10:14.120
I think one of her characters had very, very strange eyes.

10:14.220 --> 10:17.680
But Ursula Le Guin has been an influence on me from way back.

10:17.680 --> 10:20.480
And maybe that came into it to some extent, too.

10:21.840 --> 10:27.080
As far as the eyes of the Asadi go and the fact that they are a means of communication

10:27.080 --> 10:31.280
as well as a means of seeing and also a means of feeding,

10:31.280 --> 10:36.340
when you discover that they enabled these creatures to photosynthesize part of their food,

10:37.620 --> 10:42.900
I think there I was looking at the eyes in a functional sense as well as in a symbolic sense,

10:43.440 --> 10:50.300
as if they really were a physical component of their makeup that could help them survive.

10:51.860 --> 10:53.800
More with Michael Bishop on our next show.

