12:26.420 --> 12:27.560
This is Bill Vernon.

12:27.700 --> 12:28.260
And Daryl Lane.

12:28.360 --> 12:31.760
One of science fiction writer Michael Bishop's most successful short stories is

12:31.760 --> 12:35.280
Death and Designation Among the Asadi, which appeared in 1973.

12:35.760 --> 12:39.020
In 1979, Bishop published the novel Transfigurations,

12:39.200 --> 12:41.440
which was a so-called fix-up of this short story.

12:41.700 --> 12:44.300
That is, the story served as the initial third of the novel,

12:44.420 --> 12:46.280
then more material was added to continue it.

12:46.280 --> 12:48.200
Here Bishop tells us how this came about.

12:48.800 --> 12:52.320
I think when I wrote that story back in 72 or 73,

12:52.360 --> 12:55.740
that I felt that I was pretty much finished with it, that it was complete.

12:57.860 --> 13:02.780
By the time I actually undertook to do Transfigurations,

13:02.780 --> 13:08.300
I had thought some more about the characters in that story, both the humans and the aliens.

13:08.300 --> 13:12.880
And I had also done a great deal of reading on human origins,

13:14.940 --> 13:20.300
a lot of which I worked into the novel that followed that one, No Enemy But Time.

13:20.440 --> 13:28.000
But at the same time, I guess I was really kind of laying the groundwork for No Enemy But Time

13:28.000 --> 13:31.680
with the research that I did that carried me through Transfigurations.

13:32.360 --> 13:39.320
The reason that I probably expanded Transfigurations or Death and Designation among the Asadi

13:39.320 --> 13:42.500
into a full-length novel that I called Transfigurations

13:42.500 --> 13:45.340
is that by that time I was a full-time writer.

13:46.460 --> 13:49.540
I knew that this was one of my most popular stories,

13:49.540 --> 13:51.680
that there had been questions about it.

13:51.880 --> 13:54.920
Some of the loose ends had not been tied up.

13:55.360 --> 13:58.720
And I wanted to deal with the material again.

13:58.720 --> 14:03.840
And I wanted to deal with it from the perspective of my new knowledge

14:03.840 --> 14:08.900
about human origins and primate anthology, that sort of thing.

14:09.060 --> 14:12.360
So that was one of the reasons that I went ahead,

14:13.060 --> 14:16.000
used the original novella as part of the text

14:16.000 --> 14:21.640
and created a good deal of more information about new characters

14:21.640 --> 14:26.120
and a sequel to the original novella in the course of the novel.

14:27.760 --> 14:31.320
Transfigurations details an anthropological study of a group of primitive aliens.

14:31.580 --> 14:34.680
Or as Bishop warns us, we must put the primitive in quotation marks.

14:34.920 --> 14:38.320
Anthropology forms the basis for Bishop's perhaps most important novel,

14:38.540 --> 14:39.520
No Enemy But Time.

14:39.840 --> 14:42.400
This novel won the 1983 Nebula Award.

14:42.660 --> 14:46.600
The protagonist, Joshua Kampa, is capable of a sort of time travel through dreams.

14:47.060 --> 14:50.960
In No Enemy But Time, he travels to a simulacrum of Pleistocene East Africa,

14:50.960 --> 14:53.460
an African inhabited by man's distant ancestors.

14:53.660 --> 14:56.580
Campa lives among these hominids, ostensibly to study them,

14:56.740 --> 14:58.400
but he gets involved in their lives.

14:58.640 --> 15:01.880
We commented to Bishop that writing this book must have required a lot of research.

15:02.580 --> 15:07.580
I've told people that I probably did three and a half to four years of research for that book,

15:07.580 --> 15:08.980
and I believe that that's true.

15:09.200 --> 15:13.220
And by that, I don't mean that I was continuously researching and doing nothing else,

15:13.340 --> 15:16.440
not writing anything else, but only researching.

15:16.440 --> 15:22.080
But I nevertheless did spend a great, great deal of time reading material

15:22.080 --> 15:27.340
to make my proto-humans, my hominids in that book,

15:28.100 --> 15:32.400
as near to the real thing as I could imagine.

15:33.380 --> 15:38.860
So I read people like Louis B. Leakey and Mary Leakey and Richard Leakey,

15:38.940 --> 15:41.520
the entire Leakey clan, Donald Johanson,

15:42.260 --> 15:47.920
everything I could get my hands on in scientific journals and news magazines

15:47.920 --> 15:52.660
that related to new discoveries in East Africa, Tanzania, Kenya,

15:52.980 --> 15:56.580
wherever they happened to be, Ethiopia, when Donald Johanson came along.

15:56.940 --> 16:02.780
So yes, I spent an awful lot of time researching the physical nature,

16:03.200 --> 16:07.500
the stature, the possible lifestyles of these hominids,

16:07.500 --> 16:13.900
but also the flora and fauna at the same period so that I could make a credible stab

16:13.900 --> 16:19.560
at what kinds of other animals they would encounter,

16:19.820 --> 16:23.140
what kind of vegetation they would be living among,

16:23.400 --> 16:27.780
how they would have to go about their survival strategies, in other words.

16:28.080 --> 16:30.740
So yes, that took me a lot of time.

16:30.740 --> 16:33.920
I found it very, very enjoyable while I was doing,

16:34.100 --> 16:37.940
and I've really kind of put it out of my mind since then.

16:38.180 --> 16:41.220
I imagine that I may come back to it later on,

16:41.300 --> 16:43.540
but I have kind of set it aside since then.

