18:10.420 --> 18:12.160
And here are your hosts.

18:16.260 --> 18:17.480
This is David Carson.

18:17.660 --> 18:18.360
And Daryl Lane.

18:18.560 --> 18:22.180
You might have overheard some junior high or high school students talking about fighting trolls

18:22.180 --> 18:24.380
or battling an evil wizard and thought nothing of it.

18:24.520 --> 18:27.860
But you might stop and stare if you heard a lawyer or doctor saying the same thing.

18:28.040 --> 18:31.160
Well, it could happen and does most every weekend all across the U.S.,

18:31.160 --> 18:32.280
and it's spreading around the world.

18:32.540 --> 18:32.780
Right.

18:32.980 --> 18:34.760
What we're talking about is Dungeons & Dragons,

18:34.940 --> 18:37.560
a fantasy role-playing game produced by TSR Hobbies.

18:37.560 --> 18:41.620
We talked with Dr. John Eric Holmes, author of fantasy role-playing games,

18:41.780 --> 18:44.740
who edited the original basic set of rules for Dungeons & Dragons.

18:45.000 --> 18:47.200
Holmes teaches in the School of Medicine at USC.

18:47.540 --> 18:49.920
We asked him to give us a layman's description of the game.

18:51.080 --> 18:54.180
Dungeons & Dragons, or the other role-playing games,

18:54.760 --> 18:58.620
are a game where a group of people get together,

18:58.620 --> 19:05.020
and one of them devises the kind of skeleton outline of a story.

19:05.440 --> 19:09.480
In Dungeons & Dragons it would be a story about fabulous treasure

19:09.480 --> 19:13.440
or a monster in a cave or in a dungeon or something like that.

19:13.600 --> 19:19.400
And the other people, each one of them takes the part of a single adventurer.

19:20.030 --> 19:24.240
And in Dungeons & Dragons you can be an elf or a dwarf or a hobbit

19:24.240 --> 19:26.680
or a wizard or a hero.

19:28.660 --> 19:32.520
And then they pretend to go into the story

19:32.520 --> 19:35.960
and try and solve the mystery or find the treasure or whatever,

19:35.980 --> 19:38.640
and they all sit around the table and do this,

19:38.640 --> 19:45.680
and they decide how things come out if they have to decide how an event occurs

19:45.680 --> 19:50.260
by just rolling dice and consulting a table in the book to see how the things occur.

19:50.260 --> 19:54.820
So it's a story that's built up by a group of friends working together between them.

19:55.820 --> 19:57.260
That's what it is, really.

19:58.620 --> 20:01.780
Dungeons & Dragons, known as D&D, is similar to chess

20:01.780 --> 20:04.860
in that there are several different types of pieces or characters on the board.

20:05.060 --> 20:07.300
But the difference is that the players controlling the characters

20:07.300 --> 20:08.800
don't know what the whole board looks like.

20:09.120 --> 20:12.040
They only know the areas where they have been and where they are at the moment.

20:12.300 --> 20:16.100
Right. Any new area has to be explored, just as if you were really there.

20:16.280 --> 20:17.920
If you want to know what's behind a door,

20:17.920 --> 20:21.260
you tell the dungeon master that you want your character to open the door and look inside.

20:21.520 --> 20:24.000
The dungeon master, or DM, is like a referee.

20:24.300 --> 20:27.080
He knows the plot of the scenario the players are involved in

20:27.080 --> 20:29.340
and tells them of the outcome of their actions.

20:29.660 --> 20:32.340
The game can sound very involved with someone who has never played it,

20:32.400 --> 20:34.620
but most of the work is done by the dungeon master,

20:34.740 --> 20:36.080
who is usually an experienced player.

20:36.380 --> 20:40.260
The game's situation is similar to much of the fantasy literature that is popular today,

20:40.480 --> 20:41.340
but with a difference.

20:41.640 --> 20:44.160
Holmes talks about the popularity of Dungeons & Dragons

20:44.160 --> 20:46.280
and its relationship to current fantasy literature.

20:46.280 --> 20:50.540
Playing the game is different from reading a story.

20:52.120 --> 20:57.380
If you read a story, you can kind of imagine yourself being the hero,

20:57.380 --> 21:02.920
and if the story's well written, you can really get into the hero's problems

21:02.920 --> 21:07.380
and you can see the wonders that he sees and the excitement that he experiences.

21:09.720 --> 21:28.940
You can imagine how you might have handled things or what might happen if you had lived in those times.

21:28.940 --> 21:35.100
And there were a lot of people in the country at the time that Dungeons & Dragons were created

21:35.100 --> 21:40.560
who kind of had daydreams about what they would do if they were hobbits

21:40.560 --> 21:45.840
or if they were dwarves or if they were elves or heroes.

21:47.320 --> 21:57.100
And in the game, you come a lot closer to being a hobbit or a dwarf or an elf or a hero or a wizard

21:57.100 --> 22:03.500
than you do in just reading about it or that you do in just imagining it all by yourself

22:03.500 --> 22:06.560
because you have several other people playing with you,

22:06.560 --> 22:09.580
and let's say you decide that you want to be a wizard,

22:10.580 --> 22:16.420
and all your friends agree that you are a wizard or that you're a character in the game,

22:16.520 --> 22:20.620
but you start talking about that person as if it were yourself,

22:21.620 --> 22:22.600
is a wizard.

22:22.880 --> 22:28.660
And for, you know, four to six hours once a week in the evening,

22:29.180 --> 22:31.320
you feel like you really are that person.

22:31.320 --> 22:34.780
And that's a lot more exciting than just reading about such a person.

